<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911108-0102</DOCNO><DOCID>911108-0102.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Spelling Entertainment   Names Lindner, Son   To Its Top Two Posts</HL><DATE>11/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   SP WNEWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY (REC)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- Carl H. Lindner, SpellingEntertainment Inc.'s controlling shareholder, and his son, S.Craig Lindner, were named chairman and chief executiveofficer, respectively, of the entertainment concern.   The Lindners succeed Aaron Spelling, the company's68-year-old founder. Mr. Spelling said in a statement that heresigned &quot;to have more time to oversee our busy televisionproduction.&quot; He retains the titles of chairman and chiefexecutive of several Spelling Entertainment subsidaries.</LP><TEXT>   The executive changes were approved yesterday at a meetingof Spelling Entertainment's board in Los Angeles, said aspokeswoman for American Financial Corp., a Cincinnati-basedholding company owned by Mr. Lindner. She declined to commenton reasons for the changes.   American Financial owns about 53% of Jacksonville,Fla.-based Charter Co., which in turn holds an 82% stake inSpelling Entertainment. Last spring, Charter acquired Mr.Spelling's 32% stake in the company he founded. Mr. Lindneris 72 years old and his son is 36.</TEXT></DOC>